abstract.text: A view that presents data using rows in a single column.

inlineContent.text: Table views in iOS display rows of vertically scrolling content in a single column. Each row in the table contains one piece of your app’s content. For example, the Contacts app displays the name of each contact in a separate row, and the main page of the Settings app displays the available groups of settings. You can configure a table to display a single long list of rows, or you can group related rows into sections to make navigating the content easier.

Tables are common in apps with data that’s highly structured or organized hierarchically. Apps that contain hierarchical data often use tables in conjunction with a navigation view controller, which facilitates navigation between different levels of the hierarchy. For example, the Settings app uses tables and a navigation controller to organize the system settings.
manages the basic appearance of the table, but your app provides the cells (

objects) that display the actual content. The standard cell configurations display a simple combination of text and images, but you can define custom cells that display any content you want. You can also supply header and footer views to provide additional information for groups of cells.

content.text: Add a table view to your interface

inlineContent.text: To add a table view to your interface, drag a table view controller (
) object to your storyboard. Xcode creates a new scene that includes both the view controller and a table view, ready for you to configure and use.

Table views are data-driven, normally getting their data from a data source object that you provide. The data source object manages your app’s data and is responsible for creating and configuring the table’s cells. If the content of your table never changes, you can configure that content in your storyboard file instead.

content.text: Save and restore the table’s current state

inlineContent.text: Table views support UIKit app restoration. To save and restore the table’s data, assign a nonempty value to the table view’s
property. When you save its parent view controller, the table view automatically saves the index paths for the currently selected and visible rows. If the table’s data source object adopts the
protocol, the table stores the unique IDs that you provide for those items instead of their index paths.
